      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pre-Vote Commentary Influenced the Outcome</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>S J Sindeband letter holds June 18 pre-vote commentary on fight over Bedford (NY) school budget influenced vote's outcome (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the article ''Behind Bedford School Budget Fight: Economic and Ethnic Divisions'' on June 18:</p>
        <p>I was shocked to see a pre-vote commentary that the underlying issue in the budget vote was an ethnic one.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the article ''Behind Bedford School Budget Fight: Economic and Ethnic Divisions'' on June 18:</p>
        <p>I was shocked to see a pre-vote commentary that the underlying issue in the budget vote was an ethnic one.</p>
        <p>I have lived in this district for 45 years and am a former member of the school board.</p>
        <p>I have never heard even a whisper of such an issue, and every resident to whom I have spoken has expressed the same shock and surprise that The Times would publish such a charge with no back-up.</p>
        <p>This budget was opposed by many residents purely on the basis of poor fiscal management and poor administration.</p>
        <p>To what would you attribute being asked to vote for a budget that contained an item of some $160,000 to replace windows in the Pound Ridge Elementary School when the same item was part of a bond issue we approved three years ago? This is one glaring example.</p>
        <p>I am all the more offended since the budget passed on June 20, and I think The Times's low journalistic standards contributed to this miscarriage of justice at the polls.</p>
        <p>S. J. SINDEBAND  Pound Ridge</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
